The HTML code you provided has some accessibility issues. The canvas element is not accessible without additional markup to indicate the role and function of the element. Additionally, the `alt` attribute of the `<img>` element is missing, which is necessary for screen readers to provide alternative text for the image.

Here's an updated version of the code with some accessibility improvements:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Accessible HTML Code Example</title>
</head>
<body>
    <canvas id="logo" aria-label="HTML 5 logo" height="48" width="72"></canvas>
    <img src="/WAI/content-assets/wcag-act-rules/test-assets/share$" alt="HTML 5 logo" onload="loadLogo()">
    <script>
        function loadLogo() {
            const ctx = document.querySelector('#logo').getContext('2d');
            const img = new Image();
            img.src = '/WAI/content-assets/wcag-act-rules/test-assets/share$';
            img.onload = function() {
                ctx.drawImage(img, 0, 0);
            }
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```
In the updated version, the `<canvas>` element has an `aria-label` attribute to provide alternative text for screen readers. The `alt` attribute of the `<img>` element has been added to provide alternative text for the image. Additionally, the `loadLogo()` function has been added to load the image asynchronously and draw it on the canvas element. This ensures that the canvas element is accessible and can be used by screen readers.

